Description of the dataset

  • yearyear of data in this row
  • month : month of data in this row
  • day : day of data in this row
  • hour : hour of data in this row
  • season : season of data in this row
  • PM : PM2.5 concentration (ug/m^3)
  • DEWP : Dew Point (Celsius Degree)
  • TEMP : Temperature (Celsius Degree)
  • HUMI : Humidity (%)
  • PRES : Pressure (hPa)
  • cbwd : Combined wind direction
  • Iws : Cumulated wind speed (m/s)
  • precipitation : hourly precipitation (mm)
  • Iprec : Cumulated precipitation (mm)

s_time = time.time()

#To append Time, Date and hours and make a date and time object 
import datetime
def getFullDate(row):
    time = str(row['month'])+"/"+ str(row["day"])+"/"+str(row["year"])
    date = datetime.datetime.strptime(time, "%m/%d/%Y")
    time = str(row["hour"]).split(":")
    date = date.replace(hour=int(time[0]))
    return date
Beijingdata["Merged_Date_Time"] = Beijingdata.apply(getFullDate, axis=1) #.apply() function applies function along input axis of DataFrame.
Beijingdata.head()#check if the "Merged_Date_Time" column has been appended to the dataframe.

e_time = time.time()

The dataset has PM2.5 level from various loactions in beijing

  • PM_Dongsi
  • PM_Dongsihuan
  • PM_Nongzhanguan
  • PM_US Post

To perform the analysis on PM2.5 we take the the average of PM 2.5 across all the locations into column "Average_PM_Level", to depict the PM level of beijing in total.

In [9]:
s_time = time.time()

def getAverageColumn(row):
    avg = (int(row["PM_Dongsi"]) + int(row["PM_Dongsihuan"]) + int(row["PM_Nongzhanguan"]) + int(row["PM_US Post"]))/4
    return avg
Beijingdata["Average_PM_Level"] = Beijingdata.apply(getAverageColumn, axis=1)

  • Temperature has negative relation with PM level

In [14]:
#Plot the graph of PM_Level on hour for 7 days and check if the trend prevails
ListofallDays = []
for i in range(1,30):
    HourPmdatabyHour = []   
    x =  Beijingdata.loc[(Beijingdata['month'] == 10) &Beijingdata['day'].isin([i])& Beijingdata['year'].isin([2014])]
    PM_Level = x.Average_PM_Level
    if(len(x.hour) == 24):
     ListofallDays.append(PM_Level)
    
Days = range(0,24)
fig = plt.figure()
#times = Functionofsimulation(100,10000,100)
ax1 = fig.add_subplot(111)
for d in range(0,(len(ListofallDays) - 1)):
 ax1.plot(Days,ListofallDays[d], '-',label="Day-"+ str(d))
plt.xlabel('Hour')
plt.ylabel('PM_Level')
plt.legend(bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1), loc=2, borderaxespad=0.)
plt.show()

The trend of high, low, high looks prevalent across all the other days too.</b>

s_time = time.time()

import statsmodels.formula.api as sm
result = sm.ols(formula="Average_PM_Level ~ TEMP+DEWP+PRES+HUMI+Iws+Iprec+precipitation", data=Beijingdata).fit()
print (result.summary())

e_time = time.time()

print(e_time-s_time)

def Applycluster(row):
    if(int(row["hour"])<=3):
        return 1
    elif(int(row["hour"])<=10):
        return 2
    elif(int(row["hour"])<=17):
        return 0
    elif(int(row["hour"])==18):
        return 2
    elif(int(row["hour"]<=23)):
        return 1
        

Beijingdata["Hour_Cluster"] = Df.apply(Applycluster, axis=1)

        endTime = time.time()
        times[i]=endTime-startTime

In [57]:
def getPM(entry):
    PM = 20.6666 -0.0145*entry[3]-0.0174*entry[4]+0.02*entry[5]-0.005*entry[6]+0.39*entry[7]+0.20*entry[8]+0.38*entry[9]
    return PM

Recommendations

  • The regression model for our analysis showed an r-square of 34.4%. Predicting real world data with accuracy using liner models is a tough job to acheive.

  • We imporved the linear model as much as we can to account for all the possible patterns in the data and remove multicollinearity between variable, to acheive maximum precision on the predict.</b>

  • However using NON -linear modelling could be stastically appropriate analysis on the Impact of weather data on PM2.5</b>

  • We made an attempt to address this with a non - linear model, However as class dealt with only linear models, we restricted the scope of analysis only to the linear models.
